---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'Encuentros con Seres Notables';

const img1 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/encuentros-seres/encuentros-01.jpg')).default;
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="Encuentros con Seres Notables — Work"
  description="Encuentros con Seres Notables (2022). Sculpture — branches, eucalyptus, clay. Inspired by Gurdjieff. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 011</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2022 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Sculpture — branches, eucalyptus, clay &nbsp;/&nbsp; Variable dimensions</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <img src={img1.src} alt="Encuentros con Seres Notables — Hands extracting face from wall" loading="eager">
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Encuentros con Seres Notables — Brazo (sub-work detail) ]</div>
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: Encuentros con Seres Notables — Desclavada (sub-work detail) ]</div>
      </div>

      <!-- Video -->
      <div class="work-page__video">
        <div class="work-page__video-header">
          <h3>VIDEO</h3>
          <span class="label">Encuentros con Seres Notables · Full video · 2:00 min</span>
        </div>
        <video controls preload="metadata" poster="">
          <source src="/maria-elvira-escallon/video/encuentros-obra.mp4" type="video/mp4">
          Your browser does not support HTML5 video.
        </video>
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            The title is inspired by the Russian mystic George Gurdjieff's book
            <em>Meetings with Remarkable Men</em>. The exhibition explores kinship between
            humans and other living beings — trees and plants — proposing an encounter
            that dissolves the boundaries between the human body and the vegetal world.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            Escallon discovered branches that bear an uncanny resemblance to human skeletal
            anatomy — arms, joints, the articulations of a body. These found forms become
            the basis for a series of sculptures in which the distinction between the
            organic structures of trees and those of the human body becomes impossible
            to maintain. The branches are not carved or manipulated to look human; they
            simply do, revealing a morphological kinship that is both scientific and poetic.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The series includes sub-works such as <em>Brazo</em> and <em>Desclavada</em>,
            each developing specific aspects of this human-vegetal correspondence. The use
            of eucalyptus and clay alongside the found branches creates a material vocabulary
            that bridges the natural and the sculptural, the discovered and the composed.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            Gurdjieff's <em>Meetings with Remarkable Men</em> recounts the author's
            spiritual journeys and encounters with teachers who transformed his understanding
            of the world. Escallon's appropriation of the title reframes the 'remarkable
            beings' as trees and plants — shifting the encounter from the human-spiritual
            to the inter-species, proposing that the most transformative meetings may be
            those between humans and the other living forms with which we share the world.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The work extends Escallon's longstanding engagement with the vegetal world,
            begun in <em>Nuevas Floras</em> (2003), but here the relationship is inverted:
            rather than imposing human forms onto trees, the artist discovers human forms
            already present within them.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>Encuentros con Seres Notables</strong><br>
            2022<br><br>
            Sculpture.<br>
            Branches, eucalyptus, clay.<br><br>
            Variable dimensions<br><br>
            Sub-works: <em>Brazo</em>, <em>Desclavada</em>
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            [ Pending exhibition data ]
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2022). <em>Encuentros con Seres Notables</em>.
            Sculpture. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/encuentros-con-seres-notables/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>

<style>
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    }
</style>
